comment_text:
One Star ‚Äì Extremely Disappointed with After-Sale Service

I rarely write reviews, but the after-sale service for this ceiling fan has been beyond frustrating. The fan itself worked fine for about a month, and then it started making a loud clicking noise. I contacted customer support, and that‚Äôs where the real nightmare began.

It took over a week just to get a response, and even then, it was a generic reply asking for details I had already provided. After multiple follow-ups, they finally agreed to send a technician‚Äîwho never showed up. Rescheduled three times, and each time they either didn‚Äôt show up or cancelled last minute with no explanation.

It‚Äôs been nearly two months now, and the issue is still unresolved. I‚Äôve wasted time, energy, and money on something that should‚Äôve been a simple fix. Terrible customer service, no accountability, and zero urgency. I would NOT recommend this brand to anyone. Spend your money elsewhere.

author: @SumantaGarai9
comment_text: Manufacturers of BLDC fans, like Atomberg, often don‚Äôt have service engineers available to repair their own PCBs. I started installing BLDC fans back when the technology wasn‚Äôt as popular as it is today, and over time, some of those fan PCBs stopped working. Instead of offering repair services, manufacturers usually replace the entire PCB, which helps them maintain their profits. In some cases, if the fan model has been discontinued, even the replacement PCB might not be available. So, while BLDC fans can help you save on energy, they won‚Äôt necessarily save you money ‚Äî because whatever you save on electricity will likely need to be spent later on replacing a faulty PCB.
